## The Core Problem: Visibility & Ordering

In a multi-threaded Java program, two problems can occur without proper synchronization:

1. **Visibility** — changes made by one thread may not be visible to another
2. **Ordering** — the CPU/compiler may reorder instructions for optimization

```java
// Thread 1
boolean ready = false;
int value = 0;

void writer() {
    value = 42;       // write 1
    ready = true;     // write 2
}

// Thread 2 — may never see ready=true OR may see ready=true before value=42
void reader() {
    while (!ready) {}
    System.out.println(value); // could print 0!
}
```

## Atomic Classes

`java.util.concurrent.atomic` provides lock-free thread-safe operations using **CAS (Compare-And-Swap)** CPU instructions.

```java
AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger(0);

// Thread-safe increment — no synchronized needed
counter.incrementAndGet();

// CAS: only set to newVal if current value == expected
counter.compareAndSet(expected, newVal);

// AtomicReference for object references
AtomicReference<Node> head = new AtomicReference<>();
```

### Key Atomic classes:
- `AtomicInteger`, `AtomicLong`, `AtomicBoolean`
- `AtomicReference<V>`, `AtomicStampedReference<V>` (solves ABA problem)
- `LongAdder` — better than AtomicLong under high contention (striped counters)

## ReentrantLock vs synchronized

`ReentrantLock` provides everything `synchronized` does, plus:
- **Timed lock acquisition** — `tryLock(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS)`
- **Interruptible lock** — `lockInterruptibly()`
- **Fairness** — `new ReentrantLock(true)` gives waiting threads in order
- **Multiple conditions** — `Condition` objects for finer-grained wait/notify

```java
ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
Condition notFull = lock.newCondition();
Condition notEmpty = lock.newCondition();

lock.lock();
try {
    while (queue.isFull()) notFull.await();
    queue.add(item);
    notEmpty.signalAll();
} finally {
    lock.unlock(); // ALWAYS in finally!
}
```
